- @page_title = "Add-ons: Lightbox"

%h2= @page_title

:textile
  _The lightbox add-on is *available for free* in the standard player._

  The lightbox add-on displays your videos but also your images in a floating player. The lightbox-opening trigger is a simple @<a>@ element, and you can have multiple @<a>@ that open the same video or image in a lightbox.

  While it is possible to integrate SublimeVideo with other lightbox libraries (you'll need to use our "JavaScript API":/javascript-api for this), we highly recommend using SublimeVideo's lightbox add-on to get the easiest and best possible lightbox integration for your videos.

  h3(#step-1). "Step 1: Create a &lt;a&gt; element":#step-1

  bc(language-markup). <a class="sublime" href="#video1">Play the video with the ID "video1"</a>

  * @class="sublime"@ is needed.
  * @href@ must be set to "#UNIQUE_ID" where _UNIQUE_ID_ is the @DOM ID@ of the video that you'd like to open in a lightbox. *This allows you to have several links that opens the same @<video>@.*

  h3(#step-2). "Step 2: Create a &lt;video&gt; element":#step-2

  bc(language-markup). <video id="video1" style="display:none" width="640" height="360" poster="video-poster.jpg" preload="none">
    <source src="http://yoursite.com/video.mp4" />
    <source src="http://yoursite.com/video.webm" />
  </video>

  * The @DOM ID@ must corresponds to the value you've set in the @href@ of the @<a>@ element created in "Step 1":#step-1.
  * Don't add the _sublime_ @class@ to the @<video>@.
  * The @<video>@ element needs to be initially hidden.

  h3(#lightbox-settings). "Lightbox settings":#lightbox-settings

